# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: wpf-xaml
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:wpf-xaml/data-binding] In computer programming, **data-binding** is a general technique that binds data sources from the provider and consumer together and synchronizes them.
[src:wpf-xaml/data-binding] This is usually done with two data/information sources with different languages, as in XML data binding and UI data binding.
[src:wpf-xaml/data-binding] In UI data binding, data and information objects of the same language, but different logic function are bound together (e.g., Java UI elements to Java objects).
[src:wpf-xaml/data-binding] In a data binding process, each data change is reflected automatically by the elements that are bound to the data.
[src:wpf-xaml/data-binding] The term data binding is also used in cases where an outer representation of data in an element changes, and the underlying data is automatically updated to reflect this change.
[src:wpf-xaml/data-binding] As an example, a change in a `TextBox` element could modify the underlying data value.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] Direct3D (the 3D graphics API within DirectX) is widely used in the development of video games for Microsoft Windows and the Xbox line of consoles.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] Direct3D is also used by other software applications for visualization and graphics tasks such as CAD/CAM engineering.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] As Direct3D is the most widely publicized component of DirectX, it is common to see the names "DirectX" and "Direct3D" used interchangeably.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] The DirectX software development kit (SDK) consists of runtime libraries in redistributable binary form, along with accompanying documentation and headers for use in coding.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] Originally, the runtimes were only installed by games or explicitly by the user.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] Windows 95 did not launch with DirectX, but DirectX was included with Windows 95 OEM Service Release 2.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] Windows 98 and Windows NT 4.0 both shipped with DirectX, as has every version of Windows released since.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] The SDK is available as a free download.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] While the runtimes are proprietary, closed-source software, source code is provided for most of the SDK samples.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] Starting with the release of Windows 8 Developer Preview, DirectX SDK has been integrated into Windows SDK.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] In late 1994, Microsoft was ready to release Windows 95, its next operating system.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] An important factor in its value to consumers was the programs that would be able to run on it.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] There were also strong fears of compatibility; a notable case of this was from *Disney's Animated Storybook: The Lion King* which was based on the WinG programming interface.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] Due to numerous incompatible graphics drivers from new Compaq computers that were not tested with the WinG interface which came bundled with the game, it crashed so frequently on many desktop systems that parents had flooded Disney's call-in help lines.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] Another Microsoft employee, Craig Eisler, had joined the Windows 95 multimedia team to work on game technology.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] Needing program management support, Eisler recruited Eric Engstrom, and together they were granted 11 patents for their DirectX work.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] The project was codenamed the Manhattan Project, like the World War II project of the same name, and the idea was to displace the Japanese-developed video game consoles with personal computers running Microsoft's operating system.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] It had initially used the radiation symbol as its logo but Microsoft asked the team to change the logo.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] Management did not agree to the project as they were already writing off Windows as a gaming platform, but the three committed towards this project's development.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] Their rebellious nature led Brad Silverberg, the senior vice president of Microsoft's office products, to name the trio the "Beastie Boys".
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] Most of the work by the three was done among other assigned projects starting near the end of 1994.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] Within four months and with input from several hardware manufacturers, the team had developed the first set of application programming interfaces (APIs) which they presented at the 1995 Game Developers Conference.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] The SDK included libraries implementing DirectDraw for bit-mapped graphics, DirectSound for audio, and DirectPlay for communication between players over a network.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] The "Direct" part of the library was so named as these routines bypassed existing core Windows 95 routines and accessed the computer hardware only via a hardware abstraction layer (HAL).
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] Though the team had named it the "Game SDK" (software development kit), the name "DirectX" came from one journalist that had mocked the naming scheme of the various libraries.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] The team opted to continue to use that naming scheme and call the project DirectX.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] The first version of DirectX was released in September 1995 as the Windows Game SDK.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] Its DirectDraw component was the Win32 replacement for the DCI and WinG APIs for Windows 3.1.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] DirectX allowed all versions of Microsoft Windows, starting with Windows 95, to incorporate high-performance multimedia.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] Eisler wrote about the frenzy to build DirectX 1 through 5 in his blog.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] To get more developers on board DirectX, Microsoft approached id Software's John Carmack and offered to port *Doom* and *Doom 2* from MS-DOS to DirectX, free of charge, with id retaining all publishing rights to the game.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] Carmack agreed, and Microsoft's Gabe Newell led the porting project.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] The first game was released as *Doom 95* in August 1996, the first published DirectX game.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] Microsoft promoted the game heavily with Bill Gates appearing in ads for the title.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] DirectX 2.0 became a built-in component of Windows with the releases of Windows 95 OSR2 and Windows NT 4.0 in mid-1996.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] Since Windows 95 itself was still new and few games had been released for it, Microsoft engaged in heavy promotion of DirectX to developers who were generally distrustful of Microsoft's ability to build a gaming platform in Windows.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] John, the evangelist for DirectX, staged an elaborate event at the 1996 Computer Game Developers Conference which game developer Jay Barnson described as a Roman theme, including real lions, togas, and something resembling an indoor carnival.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] It was at this event that Microsoft first introduced Direct3D, and demonstrated multiplayer *MechWarrior 2* being played over the Internet.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] The DirectX team faced the challenging task of testing each DirectX release against an array of computer hardware and software.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] A variety of different graphics cards, audio cards, motherboards, CPUs, input devices, games, and other multimedia applications were tested with each beta and final release.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] The DirectX team also built and distributed tests that allowed the hardware industry to confirm that new hardware designs and driver releases would be compatible with DirectX.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] Prior to the addition of Direct3D to DirectX, Microsoft had added OpenGL to its Windows NT platform.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] OpenGL had been designed as a cross-platform, window system independent software interface to graphics hardware by Silicon Graphics, Inc. to bring 3D graphics programming into the mainstream of application programming.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] It could also be used for 2D graphics and imaging, and was controlled by the Architectural Review Board (ARB), which included Microsoft.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] Direct3D was intended to be a Microsoft controlled alternative to OpenGL, focused initially on game use.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] As 3D gaming grew, game developers discovered that OpenGL could also be used effectively for game development.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] At that point, a "battle" began between supporters of the cross-platform OpenGL and the Windows-only Direct3D.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] Incidentally, OpenGL was supported at Microsoft by the DirectX team.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] If a developer chose to use the OpenGL 3D graphics API in computer games, the other APIs of DirectX besides Direct3D were often combined with OpenGL, since OpenGL does not include all of DirectX's functionality, such as sound or joystick support.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] In a console-specific variant, Direct3D was used as a basis for Microsoft's Xbox, Xbox 360 and Xbox One console API.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] The implementation was developed jointly between Microsoft and Nvidia, which developed the custom graphics hardware used by the original Xbox.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] The Xbox API was similar to Direct3D 8.1, but is non-updateable like other console technologies.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] The Xbox was code named DirectXbox, but this was shortened to Xbox for its commercial name.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] In 2002, with the release of DirectX 9, Direct3D received support for the use of much longer shader programs than before with pixel and vertex shader version 2.0.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] Microsoft has continued to update the DirectX suite since then, introducing Shader Model 3.0 in DirectX 9.0c, released in August 2004.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] As of April 2005, DirectShow was removed from DirectX and moved to the Microsoft Platform SDK instead.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] DirectX has been confirmed to be present in Microsoft's Windows Phone 8.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] Real-time raytracing was announced as DXR in 2018.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] Support for compiling HLSL to SPIR-V was also added in the DirectX Shader Compiler the same year.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] DirectX functionality is provided in the form of COM-style objects and interfaces.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] Additionally, while not DirectX components themselves, managed objects have been built on top of some parts of DirectX, such as Managed Direct3D and the XNA graphics library on top of Direct3D 9.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] Microsoft distributes the debugging tool for DirectX called "PIX".
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] Introduced by Microsoft in 2002, DirectX 9 was a significant release in the DirectX family.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] It brought many important features and enhancements to the graphics capabilities of Windows.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] At the time of its release, it supported Windows 98, Windows Me, Windows 2000, and Windows XP.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] As of August 2024 it remains supported by all subsequent versions of Windows for backward compatibility.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] One of the key features introduced in Direct3D 9 was Shader Model 2.0, which included Pixel Shader 2.0 and Vertex Shader 2.0.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] These allowed for more complex and realistic graphics rendering.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] It also brought much needed performance improvements through better hardware acceleration capabilities, and better utilization of GPU resources.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] It also introduced HLSL, which provided a more accessible way for developers to produce shaders.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] DirectX 9 had a significant impact on game development.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] Many games from the mid-2000s to early 2010s were developed using DirectX 9 and it became a standard target for developers.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] Even today, some games still use DirectX 9 as an option for older or less powerful hardware.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] A major update to the DirectX API, DirectX 10 shipped with and was only available with Windows Vista (launched in late 2006) and later.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] Previous versions of Windows such as Windows XP are not able to run DirectX 10-exclusive applications.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] Programs running on Windows XP are limited to DirectX 9.0c, which is the latest major version available.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] The DirectPlay DPLAY.DLL was also removed and was replaced with dplayx.dll; games that rely on this DLL must duplicate it and rename it to dplay.dll.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] Direct3D 10.1 is an incremental update of Direct3D 10.0 which shipped with, and required, Windows Vista Service Pack 1, which was released in February 2008.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] This release mainly sets a few more image quality standards for graphics vendors, while giving developers more control over image quality.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] It also adds support for cube map arrays, separate blend modes per-MRT, coverage mask export from a pixel shader, ability to run pixel shader per sample, access to multi-sampled depth buffers and requires that the video card supports Shader Model 4.1 or higher and 32-bit floating-point operations.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] Direct3D 10.1 still fully supports Direct3D 10 hardware, but in order to utilize all of the new features, updated hardware is required.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] Microsoft unveiled DirectX 11 at the Gamefest 08 event in Seattle.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] The Final Platform Update launched for Windows Vista on October 27, 2009, which was a week after the initial release of Windows 7, which launched with Direct3D 11 as a base standard.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] Major scheduled features including GPGPU software support (DirectCompute), and Direct3D 11 with tessellation support and improved multi-threading support to assist video game developers in developing games that better utilize multi-core processors.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] Parts of the new API such as multi-threaded resource handling can be supported on Direct3D 9/10/10.1-class hardware.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] Hardware tessellation and Shader Model 5.0 require Direct3D 11 supporting hardware.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] Direct3D 11 is a strict superset of Direct3D 10.1 — all hardware and API features of version 10.1 are retained, and new features are added only when necessary for exposing new functionality.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] This helps to keep backward compatibility with previous versions of Direct3D.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] DirectX 12 was announced by Microsoft at GDC on March 20, 2014, and was officially launched alongside Windows 10 on July 29, 2015.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] The primary feature highlight for the new release of DirectX was the introduction of advanced low-level programming with Direct3D 12, which can reduce driver overhead.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] Developers are now able to implement their own command lists and buffers to the GPU, allowing for more efficient resource utilization through parallel computation.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] Lead developer Max McMullen stated that the main goal of Direct3D 12 is to achieve "console-level efficiency on phone, tablet and PC".
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] The release of Direct3D 12 comes alongside other initiatives for low-overhead graphics APIs including AMD's Mantle for AMD graphics cards, Apple's Metal for iOS and macOS and Khronos Group's cross-platform Vulkan.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] Multiadapter support will feature in Direct3D 12 allowing developers to utilize multiple GPUs on a system simultaneously; multi-GPU (mGPU) support was previously dependent on vendor implementations such as AMD CrossFireX or NVIDIA SLI.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] Direct3D 12 is supported on all Fermi and later Nvidia GPUs, on AMD's GCN-based chips and on Intel's Haswell and later processors' graphics units.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] At SIGGRAPH 2014, Intel released a demo showing a computer generated asteroid field, in which Direct3D 12 was claimed to be 50–70% more efficient than Direct3D 11 in rendering speed and CPU power consumption.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] The performance improvements of Direct3D 12 on the Xbox are not as substantial as on the PC.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] In March 2018, DirectX Raytracing (DXR) was announced, capable of real-time ray-tracing on supported hardware, and the DXR API was added in the Windows 10 October 2018 update.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] In 2019 Microsoft announced the arrival of DirectX 12 to Windows 7 but only as a plug-in for certain game titles.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] Microsoft revealed DirectX 12 Ultimate in March 2020.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] DirectX 12 Ultimate will unify to a common library on both Windows 10 computers and the Xbox Series X and other ninth-generation Xbox consoles.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] Among the new features in Ultimate includes DirectX Raytracing 1.1, Variable Rate Shading, which gives programmers control over the level of detail of shading depending on design choices, Mesh Shaders, and Sampler Feedback.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] The version number as reported by Microsoft's DxDiag tool (version 4.09.0000.0900 and higher) use the x.xx.xxxx.xxxx format for version numbers.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] However, the DirectX and Windows XP MSDN page claims that the registry always has been in the x.xx.xx.xxxx format.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] Therefore, when the above table lists a version as '4.09.00.0904' Microsoft's DxDiag tool may have it as '4.09.0000.0904'.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] APIs such as Direct3D and DirectSound need to interact with hardware, and they do this through a device driver.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] Hardware manufacturers have to write these drivers for a particular DirectX version's device driver interface (or DDI), and test each individual piece of hardware to make them DirectX compatible.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] Some hardware devices have only DirectX compatible drivers (in other words, one must install DirectX in order to use that hardware).
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] Early versions of DirectX included an up-to-date library of all of the DirectX compatible drivers currently available.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] This practice was stopped however, in favor of the web-based Windows Update driver-update system, which allowed users to download only the drivers relevant to their hardware, rather than the entire library.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] Prior to DirectX 10, DirectX runtime was designed to be *backward compatible* with older drivers, meaning that newer versions of the APIs were designed to interoperate with older drivers written against a previous version's DDI.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] The application programmer had to query the available hardware capabilities using a complex system of "cap bits" each tied to a particular hardware feature.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] Direct3D 7 and earlier would work on any version of the DDI, Direct3D 8 requires a minimum DDI level of 6 and Direct3D 9 requires a minimum DDI level of 7.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] However, the Direct3D 10 runtime in Windows Vista cannot run on older hardware drivers due to the significantly updated DDI, which requires a unified feature set and abandons the use of "cap bits".
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] Direct3D 10.1 introduces "feature levels" 10_0 and 10_1, which allow use of only the hardware features defined in the specified version of Direct3D API.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] Feature level 11_1 has been introduced with Direct3D 11.1.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] In 2002, Microsoft released a version of DirectX compatible with the Microsoft .NET Framework, thus allowing programmers to take advantage of DirectX functionality from within .NET applications using compatible languages such as managed C++ or the use of the C# programming language.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] This API was known as "Managed DirectX" (or MDX for short), and claimed to operate at 98% of performance of the underlying native DirectX APIs.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] In December 2005, February 2006, April 2006, and August 2006, Microsoft released successive updates to this library, culminating in a beta version called Managed DirectX 2.0.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] While Managed DirectX 2.0 consolidated functionality that had previously been scattered over multiple assemblies into a single assembly, thus simplifying dependencies on it for software developers, development on this version has subsequently been discontinued, and it is no longer supported.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] The Managed DirectX 2.0 library expired on October 5, 2006.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] During the GDC 2006, Microsoft presented the XNA Framework, a new managed version of DirectX (similar but not identical to Managed DirectX) that is intended to assist development of games by making it easier to integrate DirectX, HLSL and other tools in one package.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] It also supports the execution of managed code on the Xbox 360.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] The XNA Game Studio Express RTM was made available on December 11, 2006, as a free download for Windows XP.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] Unlike the DirectX runtime, Managed DirectX, XNA Framework or the Xbox 360 APIs (XInput, XACT etc.) have not shipped as part of Windows.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] Developers are expected to redistribute the runtime components along with their games or applications.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] No Microsoft product including the latest XNA releases provides DirectX 10 support for the .NET Framework.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] There are alternatives to the DirectX family of APIs, with OpenGL, its successor Vulkan, Metal and Mantle having the most features comparable to Direct3D.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] Examples of other APIs include SDL, Allegro, OpenMAX, OpenML, OpenAL, OpenCL, FMOD, SFML etc.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] Many of these libraries are cross-platform or have open codebases.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] There are also alternative implementations that aim to provide the same API, such as the one in Wine.
[src:wpf-xaml/directx] Furthermore, the developers of ReactOS are trying to reimplement DirectX under the name "ReactX".
[src:wpf-xaml/extensible-application-markup-language] XAML is used extensively in Windows Presentation Foundation (WPF), Silverlight, Workflow Foundation (WF), Windows UI Library (WinUI), Universal Windows Platform (UWP), and .NET Multi-platform App UI (.NET MAUI).
[src:wpf-xaml/extensible-application-markup-language] In WPF and UWP, XAML is a user interface markup language to define UI elements, data binding, and events.
[src:wpf-xaml/extensible-application-markup-language] XAML elements map directly to Common Language Runtime (CLR) object instances, while XAML attributes map to CLR properties and events on those objects.
[src:wpf-xaml/extensible-application-markup-language] Anything that is created or implemented in XAML can be expressed using a more traditional .NET language, such as C# or Visual Basic .NET.
[src:wpf-xaml/extensible-application-markup-language] However, a key aspect of the technology is the reduced complexity needed for tools to process XAML, because it is based on XML.
[src:wpf-xaml/extensible-application-markup-language] XAML originally stood for Extensible Avalon Markup Language, *Avalon* being the code-name for Windows Presentation Foundation (WPF).
[src:wpf-xaml/extensible-application-markup-language] Before the end of .NET Framework 3.0 development, however, Microsoft adopted XAML for Workflow Foundation (WF).
[src:wpf-xaml/extensible-application-markup-language] In WPF, XAML describes visual user interfaces.
[src:wpf-xaml/extensible-application-markup-language] WPF allows for the definition of both 2D and 3D objects, rotations, animations, and a variety of other effects and features.
[src:wpf-xaml/extensible-application-markup-language] A XAML file can be compiled into a Binary Application Markup Language (BAML) file, which may be inserted as a resource into a .NET Framework assembly.
[src:wpf-xaml/extensible-application-markup-language] At run-time, the framework engine extracts the BAML file from assembly resources, parses it, and creates a corresponding WPF visual tree or workflow.
[src:wpf-xaml/extensible-application-markup-language] In WF contexts, XAML describes potentially long-running declarative logic, such as those created by process modeling tools and rules systems.
[src:wpf-xaml/extensible-application-markup-language] The serialization format for workflows was previously called XOML, to differentiate it from UI markup use of XAML, but now they are no longer distinguished.
[src:wpf-xaml/extensible-application-markup-language] However, the file extension for files containing the workflow markup is still ".xoml".
[src:wpf-xaml/extensible-application-markup-language] XAML uses a specific way to define look and feel called *Template*s; differing from Cascading Style Sheet syntax, it is closer to XBL.
[src:wpf-xaml/extensible-application-markup-language] To create XAML files, one could use Microsoft Expression Blend, Microsoft Visual Studio, the hostable WF visual designer, or XAMLPad.
[src:wpf-xaml/extensible-application-markup-language] This Windows Presentation Foundation example shows the text "Hello, world!" in the top-level XAML container called Canvas.
[src:wpf-xaml/extensible-application-markup-language] The schema (the `xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/..."` part) may have to be changed to work on some computers.
[src:wpf-xaml/extensible-application-markup-language] A crucial part of utilizing XAML to its full potential is making appropriate usage of binding, as well as creating custom user elements as required.
[src:wpf-xaml/extensible-application-markup-language] These versions have some differences in the parsing behavior.
[src:wpf-xaml/extensible-application-markup-language] Additionally, the Silverlight 4 XAML parser is not 100% backward-compatible with Silverlight 3 files.
[src:wpf-xaml/extensible-application-markup-language] Silverlight 3 XAML files may be rejected or parsed differently by the Silverlight 4 parser.
[src:wpf-xaml/extensible-application-markup-language] Besides Microsoft implementations, there is also OpenSilver (formerly known as CSHTML5), a contemporary web technology implementation.
[src:wpf-xaml/extensible-application-markup-language] Historically, XAML based applications could be run in some web browsers, such as Internet Explorer and Firefox.
[src:wpf-xaml/extensible-application-markup-language] This could be achieved through XBAP files created from WPF applications, or via the Silverlight browser plugin.
[src:wpf-xaml/extensible-application-markup-language] However, both these methods are now unsupported on all major browsers due to their reliance on the discontinued NPAPI browser plugin interface.
[src:wpf-xaml/extensible-application-markup-language] In 2007, European Committee for Interoperable Systems (ECIS) – a coalition of mostly American software companies – accused Microsoft of attempting to hijack HTML and replace it with XAML, thus creating a vendor lock-in.
[src:wpf-xaml/extensible-application-markup-language] Jeremy Reimer, writing for *Ars Technica* described this comment as "the most egregious error" and added that XAML is unlikely to ever replace HTML.
[src:wpf-xaml/model-view-viewmodel] The *viewmodel* of MVVM is a value converter, meaning it is responsible for exposing (converting) the data objects from the model in such a way they can be easily managed and presented.
[src:wpf-xaml/model-view-viewmodel] In this respect, the viewmodel is more *model* than *view*, and handles most (if not all) of the view's display logic.
[src:wpf-xaml/model-view-viewmodel] The viewmodel may implement a mediator pattern, organizing access to the back-end logic around the set of use cases supported by the view.
[src:wpf-xaml/model-view-viewmodel] MVVM is a variation of Martin Fowler's Presentation Model design pattern.
[src:wpf-xaml/model-view-viewmodel] MVVM is very similar to the Model-view-presenter pattern.
[src:wpf-xaml/model-view-viewmodel] It was invented by Microsoft architects Ken Cooper and Ted Peters specifically to simplify event-driven programming of user interfaces.
[src:wpf-xaml/model-view-viewmodel] The pattern was incorporated into the Windows Presentation Foundation (WPF) (Microsoft's .NET graphics system) and Silverlight, WPF's Internet application derivative.
[src:wpf-xaml/model-view-viewmodel] John Gossman, a Microsoft WPF and Silverlight architect, announced MVVM on his blog in 2005.
[src:wpf-xaml/model-view-viewmodel] Model–view–viewmodel is also referred to as **model–view–binder**, especially in implementations not involving the .NET platform.
[src:wpf-xaml/model-view-viewmodel] ZK, a web application framework written in Java, and the JavaScript library KnockoutJS use model–view–binder.
[src:wpf-xaml/model-view-viewmodel] , which represents content (a data-centric approach).
[src:wpf-xaml/model-view-viewmodel] is the structure, layout, and appearance of what a user sees on the screen.
[src:wpf-xaml/model-view-viewmodel] (properties, event callbacks, etc.) that is defined to link the view and view model.
[src:wpf-xaml/model-view-viewmodel] is an abstraction of the view exposing public properties and commands.
[src:wpf-xaml/model-view-viewmodel] , which automates communication between the view and its bound properties in the view model.
[src:wpf-xaml/model-view-viewmodel] The view model has been described as a state of the data in the model.
[src:wpf-xaml/model-view-viewmodel] The main difference between the view model and the Presenter in the MVP pattern is that the presenter has a reference to a view, whereas the view model does not.
[src:wpf-xaml/model-view-viewmodel] Instead, a view directly binds to properties on the view model to send and receive updates.
[src:wpf-xaml/model-view-viewmodel] Declarative data and command-binding are implicit in the MVVM pattern.
[src:wpf-xaml/model-view-viewmodel] The binder frees the developer from being obliged to write boiler-plate logic to synchronize the view model and view.
[src:wpf-xaml/model-view-viewmodel] and without a binder, one would typically use MVP or MVC instead and have to write more boilerplate (or generate it with some other tool).
[src:wpf-xaml/model-view-viewmodel] MVVM was designed to remove virtually all GUI code ("code-behind") from the view layer, by using data binding functions in WPF (Windows Presentation Foundation) to better facilitate the separation of view layer development from the rest of the pattern.
[src:wpf-xaml/model-view-viewmodel] Instead of requiring user experience (UX) developers to write GUI code, they can use the framework markup language (e.g.
[src:wpf-xaml/model-view-viewmodel] XAML) and create data bindings to the view model, which is written and maintained by application developers.
[src:wpf-xaml/model-view-viewmodel] The separation of roles allows interactive designers to focus on UX needs rather than programming of business logic.
[src:wpf-xaml/model-view-viewmodel] The layers of an application can thus be developed in multiple work streams for higher productivity.
[src:wpf-xaml/model-view-viewmodel] Even when a single developer works on the entire codebase, a proper separation of the view from the model is more productive, as the user interface typically changes frequently and late in the development cycle based on end-user feedback.
[src:wpf-xaml/model-view-viewmodel] The MVVM pattern attempts to gain both advantages of separation of functional development provided by MVC, while leveraging the advantages of data bindings and the framework by binding data as close to the pure application model as possible.
[src:wpf-xaml/model-view-viewmodel] It uses the binder, view model, and any business layers' data-checking features to validate incoming data.
[src:wpf-xaml/model-view-viewmodel] The result is that the model and framework drive as much of the operations as possible, eliminating or minimizing application logic which directly manipulates the view (e.g., code-behind).
[src:wpf-xaml/model-view-viewmodel] John Gossman has criticized the MVVM pattern and its application in specific uses, stating that MVVM can be "overkill" when creating simple user interfaces.
[src:wpf-xaml/model-view-viewmodel] For larger applications, he believes that generalizing the viewmodel upfront can be difficult, and that large-scale data binding can lead to lower performance.
[src:wpf-xaml/model-view-viewmodel] The following are simple examples of an implementation of the MVVM pattern.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] The **.NET Framework** (pronounced "*dot net*") is a proprietary software framework developed by Microsoft that runs primarily on Microsoft Windows.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] It was the predominant implementation of the Common Language Infrastructure (CLI) until being superseded by the cross-platform .NET project.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] It includes a large class library called Framework Class Library (FCL) and provides language interoperability (each language can use code written in other languages) across several programming languages.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] Programs written for .NET Framework execute in a software environment (in contrast to a hardware environment) named the Common Language Runtime (CLR).
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] The CLR is an application virtual machine that provides services such as security, memory management, and exception handling.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] As such, computer code written using .NET Framework is called "managed code".
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] FCL and CLR together constitute the .NET Framework.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] FCL provides the user interface, data access, database connectivity, cryptography, web application development, numeric algorithms, and network communications.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] Programmers produce software by combining their source code with the .NET Framework and other libraries.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] The framework is intended to be used by most new applications created for the Windows platform.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] Microsoft also produces an integrated development environment for .NET software called Visual Studio.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] .NET Framework began as proprietary software, although the firm worked to standardize the software stack almost immediately, even before its first release.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] Despite the standardization efforts, developers, mainly those in the free and open-source software communities, expressed their unease with the selected terms and the prospects of any free and open-source implementation, especially regarding software patents.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] Since then, Microsoft has changed .NET development to more closely follow a contemporary model of a community-developed software project, including issuing an update to its patent promising to address the concerns.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] In April 2019, Microsoft released .NET Framework 4.8, the last major version of the framework as a proprietary offering, followed by .NET Framework 4.8.1 in August 2022.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] Only monthly security and reliability bug fixes to that version have been released since then.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] No further changes to that version are planned.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] The .NET Framework will continue to be included with future releases of Windows and continue to receive security updates, with no plans to remove it as of July 2025.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] Microsoft began developing .NET Framework in the late 1990s, originally under the name of Next Generation Windows Services (NGWS), as part of the Microsoft .NET strategy.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] By early 2000, the first beta versions of .NET 1.0 were released.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] In August 2000, Microsoft and Intel worked to standardize Common Language Infrastructure (CLI) and C#.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] By December 2001, both were ratified as ECMA standards.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] International Organization for Standardization (ISO) followed in April 2003.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] The current version of ISO standards are ISO/IEC 23271:2012 and ISO/IEC 23270:2006.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] While Microsoft and their partners hold patents for CLI and C#, ECMA and ISO require that all patents essential to implementation be made available under "reasonable and non-discriminatory terms".
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] The firms agreed to meet these terms, and to make the patents available royalty-free.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] However, this did not apply to the part of the .NET Framework not covered by ECMA-ISO standards, which included Windows Forms, ADO.NET, and ASP.NET.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] Patents that Microsoft holds in these areas may have deterred non-Microsoft implementations of the full framework.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] Windows Vista is the first client version of Windows that integrated the .NET Framework.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] On October 3, 2007, Microsoft announced that the source code for .NET Framework 3.5 libraries was to become available under the Microsoft Reference Source License (Ms-RSL).
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] The source code repository became available online on January 16, 2008, and included BCL, ASP.NET, ADO.NET, Windows Forms, WPF, and XML.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] Scott Guthrie of Microsoft promised that LINQ, WCF, and WF libraries were being added.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] The .NET Compact Framework and .NET Micro Framework variants of the .NET Framework provided support for other Microsoft platforms such as Windows Mobile, Windows CE and other resource-constrained embedded devices.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] Silverlight provided support for web browsers via plug-ins.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] In November 2014, Microsoft also produced an update to its patent grants, which further extends the scope beyond its prior pledges.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] Prior projects like Mono existed in a legal gray area because Microsoft's earlier grants applied only to the technology in "covered specifications", including strictly the 4th editions each of ECMA-334 and ECMA-335.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] The new patent promise, however, places no ceiling on the specification version, and even extends to any .NET runtime technologies documented on MSDN that have not been formally specified by the ECMA group, if a project chooses to implement them.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] This allows Mono and other projects to maintain feature parity with modern .NET features that have been introduced since the 4th edition was published all without being at risk of patent litigation over the implementation of those features.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] The new grant does maintain the restriction that any implementation must maintain minimum compliance with the mandatory parts of the CLI specification.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] On March 31, 2016, Microsoft announced at Microsoft Build that they will completely relicense Mono under an MIT License even in scenarios where formerly a commercial license was needed.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] Microsoft also supplemented its prior patent promise for Mono, stating that they will not assert any "applicable patents" against parties that are "using, selling, offering for sale, importing, or distributing Mono." It was announced that the Mono Project was contributed to the .NET Foundation.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] These developments followed the acquisition of Xamarin, which began in February 2016 and was finished on March 18, 2016.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] Microsoft's press release highlights that the cross-platform commitment now allows for a fully open-source, modern server-side .NET stack.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] Microsoft released the source code for WPF, Windows Forms and WinUI on December 4, 2018.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] Common Language Infrastructure (CLI) provides a language-neutral platform for application development and execution.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] By implementing the core aspects of .NET Framework within the scope of CLI, these functions will not be tied to one language but will be available across the many languages supported by the framework.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] .NET Framework includes the Common Language Runtime (CLR).
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] It serves as the execution engine of .NET Framework and offers many services such as memory management, type safety, exception handling, garbage collection, security and thread management.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] All programs written for .NET Framework are executed by the CLR.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] Programs written for .NET Framework are compiled into Common Intermediate Language code (CIL), as opposed to being directly compiled into machine code.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] During execution, an architecture-specific just-in-time compiler (JIT) turns the CIL code into machine code.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] Compiled CLI code is stored in CLI assemblies.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] As mandated by the specification, assemblies are stored in Portable Executable (PE) file format, common on Windows platform for all *dynamic-link library* (DLL) and *executable* EXE files.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] Each assembly consists of one or more files, one of which must contain a manifest bearing the metadata for the assembly.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] The complete name of an assembly (not to be confused with the file name on disk) contains its simple text name, version number, culture, and public key token.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] Assemblies are considered equivalent if they share the same complete name.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] A private key can also be used by the creator of the assembly for strong naming.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] The public key token determines the real-world identity of the assembly's signer.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] Only those knowing their private key (of the double-key cryptography system) can sign assemblies that have the same strong name as a prior version assembly.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] Strong naming is required to add assemblies to Global Assembly Cache.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] Starting with Visual Studio 2015, .NET Native compilation technology allows for the compilation of .NET code of Universal Windows Platform apps directly to machine code rather than CIL code, but the app must be written in either C# or Visual Basic.NET.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] .NET Framework includes an implementation of the CLI foundational Standard Libraries.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] The .NET Framework Class Library (FCL) is organized in a hierarchy of namespaces.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] Most of the built-in application programming interfaces (APIs) are part of either `System.*` or `Microsoft.*` namespaces.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] These class libraries implement many common functions, such as file reading and writing, graphic rendering, database interaction, and XML document manipulation.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] The class libraries are available for all CLI compliant languages.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] The FCL implements the CLI Base Class Library (BCL) and other class libraries—some are specified by CLI and others are Microsoft specific.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] BCL includes a small subset of the entire class library and is the core set of classes that serve as the basic API of CLR.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] For .NET Framework most classes considered being part of BCL reside in `mscorlib.dll`, `System.dll` and `System.Core.dll`.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] BCL classes are available in .NET Framework as well as in CLI's alternative implementations, including .NET Compact Framework, Microsoft Silverlight, .NET Core and Mono.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] FCL refers to the entire class library that ships with .NET Framework.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] It includes BCL, an expanded set of libraries, including Windows Forms, ASP.NET, and Windows Presentation Foundation (WPF), and also extensions to the base class libraries ADO.NET, Language Integrated Query (LINQ), Windows Communication Foundation (WCF), and Workflow Foundation (WF).
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] FCL is much larger in scope than standard libraries for languages like C++, and comparable in scope to standard libraries of Java.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] With the introduction of alternative CLI's implementations (e.g., Silverlight), Microsoft introduced the concept of Portable Class Libraries (PCL) allowing a consuming library to run on more than one implementation.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] With the further proliferation of implementations, the PCL approach failed to scale (PCLs are defined intersections of API surface between two or more implementations).
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] As the next evolutionary step of PCL, the .NET Standard Library was created retroactively based on the `System.Runtime.dll` based APIs found in UWP and Silverlight.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] New CLI's implementations are encouraged to implement a version of the Standard Library allowing them to run existent third-party libraries with no need of creating new versions of them.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] The .NET Standard Library allows an independent evolution of the library and app model layers within the .NET architecture.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] NuGet is the package manager for all .NET platforms.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] It is used to retrieve third-party libraries into a .NET project with a global library feed at NuGet.org.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] Private feeds can be maintained separately, e.g., by a build server or a file system directory.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] Microsoft introduced C++/CLI in Visual Studio 2005, which is a language and means of compiling Visual C++ programs to run within the .NET Framework.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] Some parts of the C++ program still run within an unmanaged Visual C++ Runtime, while specially modified parts are translated into CIL code and run with the .NET Framework's CLR.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] Assemblies compiled using the C++/CLI compiler are termed mixed-mode assemblies since they contain native and managed code in the same DLL.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] Such assemblies are more complex to reverse engineer since .NET decompilers such as .NET Reflector reveal only the managed code.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] Because computer systems commonly require interaction between newer and older applications, .NET Framework provides means to access functions implemented in newer and older programs that execute outside .NET environment.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] Access to Component Object Model (COM) components is provided in `System.Runtime.InteropServices` and `System.EnterpriseServices` namespaces of the framework.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] Access to other functions is via Platform Invocation Services (P/Invoke).
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] Access to .NET functions from native applications is via the reverse P/Invoke function.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] .NET Framework introduces a Common Type System (CTS) that defines all possible data types and programming constructs supported by CLR and how they may or may not interact conforming to CLI specifications.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] Because of this feature, .NET Framework supports the exchange of types and object instances between libraries and applications written using any conforming CLI language.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] CTS and the CLR used in .NET Framework also enforce type safety.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] This prevents ill-defined casts, wrong method invocations, and memory size issues when accessing an object.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] This also makes most CLI languages statically typed (with or without type inference).
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] However, starting with .NET Framework 4.0, the Dynamic Language Runtime extended the CLR, allowing dynamically typed languages to be implemented atop the CLI.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] While Microsoft has never implemented the full framework on any system except Microsoft Windows, it has engineered the framework to be cross-platform, and implementations are available for other operating systems (see Silverlight and § Alternative implementations).
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] Microsoft submitted the specifications for CLI (which includes the Base Class Libraries, CTS, and CIL), C#, and C++/CLI to both Ecma International (ECMA) and International Organization for Standardization (ISO), making them available as official standards.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] This makes it possible for third parties to create compatible implementations of the framework and its languages on other platforms.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] Core cross-platform .NET (formerly .NET Core) is officially available also for many Linux distributions and macOS.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] .NET Framework has its own security mechanism with two general features: Code Access Security (CAS), and validation and verification.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] CAS is based on evidence that is associated with a specific assembly.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] Typically, the evidence is the source of the assembly (whether it is installed on the local machine or has been downloaded from the Internet).
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] CAS uses evidence to determine the permissions granted to the code.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] When calling code demands that it be granted a specific permission, CLR performs a call stack walk checking every assembly of each method in the call stack for the required permission; if any assembly is not granted the permission, it will throw a security exception.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] Managed CIL bytecode is easier to reverse-engineer than native code, unless obfuscated. .NET decompiler programs enable developers with no reverse-engineering skills to view the source code behind unobfuscated .NET assemblies.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] In contrast, apps compiled from native machine code are much harder to reverse-engineer, and source code is almost never produced successfully, mainly because of compiler optimizations and lack of reflection.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] This creates concerns in the business community over the possible loss of trade secrets and the bypassing of license control mechanisms.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] To mitigate this, Microsoft has included Dotfuscator Community Edition with Visual Studio .NET since 2002.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] Third-party obfuscation tools are also available from vendors such as VMware, V.i.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] Method-level encryption tools for .NET code are available from vendors such as SafeNet.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] CLR frees the developer from the burden of managing memory (allocating and freeing up when done); it handles memory management itself by detecting when memory can be safely freed.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] Instantiations of .NET types (objects) are allocated from the managed heap; a pool of memory managed by CLR.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] As long as a reference to an object exists, which may be either direct, or via a graph of objects, the object is considered to be in use.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] When no reference to an object exists, and it cannot be reached or used, it becomes garbage, eligible for collection.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] .NET Framework includes a garbage collector (GC) which runs periodically, on a separate thread from the application's thread, that enumerates all the unusable objects and reclaims the memory allocated to them.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] It is a non-deterministic, compacting, mark-and-sweep garbage collector.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] GC runs only when a set amount of memory has been used or there is enough pressure for memory on the system.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] Since it is not guaranteed when the conditions to reclaim memory are reached, GC runs are non-deterministic.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] Each .NET application has a set of roots, which are pointers to objects on the managed heap (*managed objects*).
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] These include references to static objects, objects defined as local variables or method parameters currently in scope, and objects referred to by CPU registers.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] When GC runs, it pauses the application and then, for each object referred to in the root, it recursively enumerates all the objects reachable from the root objects and marks them as reachable.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] It uses CLI metadata and reflection to discover the objects encapsulated by an object, and then recursively walk them.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] It then enumerates all the objects on the heap (which were initially allocated contiguously) using reflection.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] All objects not marked as reachable are garbage.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] Since the memory held by garbage is of no consequence, it is considered free space.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] However, this leaves chunks of free space between objects which were initially contiguous.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] The objects are then *compacted* together to make free space on the managed heap contiguous again.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] Any reference to an object invalidated by moving the object is updated by GC to reflect the new location.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] The application is resumed after garbage collection ends.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] The latest version of .NET framework uses concurrent garbage collection along with user code, making pauses unnoticeable, because it is done in the background.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] The garbage collector used by .NET Framework is also *generational*.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] Newly created objects are tagged *Generation 0*.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] Objects that survive one garbage collection are tagged *Generation 1*.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] Generation 1 objects that survive another collection are *Generation 2*.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] The framework uses up to Generation 2 objects.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] Higher generation objects are garbage collected less often than lower generation objects.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] This raises the efficiency of garbage collection, as older objects tend to have longer lifetimes than newer objects.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] By ignoring older objects in most collection runs, fewer checks and compaction operations are needed in total.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] When an application is first launched, the .NET Framework compiles the CIL code into executable code using its just-in-time compiler, and caches the executable program into the .NET Native Image Cache.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] Due to caching, the application launches faster for subsequent launches, although the first launch is usually slower.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] To speed up the first launch, developers may use the Native Image Generator utility to manually ahead-of-time compile and cache any .NET application.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] The garbage collector, which is integrated into the environment, can introduce unanticipated delays of execution over which the developer has little direct control.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] .NET Framework provides support for calling Streaming SIMD Extensions (SSE) via managed code from April 2014 in Visual Studio 2013 Update 2.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] However, Mono has provided support for SIMD Extensions as of version 2.2 within the Mono.Simd namespace in 2009.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] Mono's lead developer Miguel de Icaza has expressed hope that this SIMD support will be adopted by CLR's ECMA standard.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] Streaming SIMD Extensions have been available in x86 CPUs since the introduction of the Pentium III.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] Some other architectures such as ARM and MIPS also have SIMD extensions.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] In case the CPU lacks support for those extensions, the instructions are simulated in software.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] .NET Framework was the predominant implementation of CLI, until the release of .NET.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] Other implementations for parts of the framework exist.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] Although the runtime engine is described by an ECMA-ISO specification, other implementations of it may be encumbered by patent issues; ISO standards may include the disclaimer, "Attention is drawn to the possibility that some of the elements of this document may be the subject of patent rights.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] ISO shall not be held responsible for identifying any or all such patent rights." It is harder to develop alternatives to FCL, which is not described by an open standard and may be subject to copyright restrictions.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] Also, parts of FCL have Windows-specific functions and behavior, so implementation on non-Windows platforms can be problematic.
[src:wpf-xaml/net-framework] Some alternative implementations of parts of the framework are listed here.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] Originally developed by Microsoft, WPF was initially released as part of .NET Framework 3.0 in 2006.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] In 2018, Microsoft released WPF as open source under the MIT License.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] WPF's design and its layout language XAML have been adopted by multiple other UI frameworks, such as UWP, .NET MAUI, and Avalonia.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] WPF employs XAML, an XML-based language, to define and link various interface elements, and uses C# to define program behavior.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] WPF applications are deployed as standalone desktop programs.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] WPF supports a number of common user interface elements, such as 2D/3D rendering, fixed and adaptive documents, typography, vector graphics, runtime animation, and pre-rendered media.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] These elements can then be linked and manipulated based on various events, user interactions, and data bindings.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] WPF was developed under the codename "Avalon", as part of the WinFX programming model for Windows "Longhorn".
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] In August 2004, Microsoft announced that components of WinFX would be backported to Windows XP and Windows Server 2003.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] It would later be released as part of .NET Framework 3.0, a free download for these operating systems.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] WPF runtime libraries are included with all versions of Microsoft Windows since Windows Vista and Windows Server 2008.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] At the Microsoft Connect event on December 4, 2018, Microsoft announced releasing WPF as open source project on GitHub.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] Windows Presentation Foundation has become available for projects targeting the .NET software framework, however, the system is not cross-platform and is still available only on Windows.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] In WPF, screens and other UI elements are defined using a pair of files: a XAML file and an associated C# file with the extension `.xaml.cs`, often referred to as a "code-behind".
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] The XAML file declaratively defines the layout, contents and other properties of the UI element, while the C# file allows exposure of code entry points for interactivity.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] In the above example, a UI element called `MainWindow` is declared as a subclass of the built-in `Window` class.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] The XAML file defines the layout, which in this example is a vertical collection of controls - a textblock outlining instructions to the user, a textbox for the user to type their name, a button to submit, and a results text block.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] When the button is clicked, the method `SubmitButton_Click` is called, which is defined in the `.xaml.cs` file.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] This function updates the final textblock to contain a message greeting the user, addressing them by their submitted name.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] WPF supports most modern media types, including vector and raster images, audio, video, and can support both 2D and 3D rendering.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] It also supports implementing graphical effects on visual elements, such as HLSL pixel shaders and built-in effects such as blurs and drop shadows.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] WPF mainly relies on vector graphics, which allows most controls and elements to be scaled without loss in quality or pixelization.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] WPF employs data binding, a technique of propagating changes between user interface elements and the object model of the program.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] This would make the textblock display the value of the `Username` property.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] The direction data binding happens is configurable - it can be defined to go UI-to-source (eg. text entered into a textbox being propagated to a bound string property in code), or source-to-UI (eg. a visual clock being updated to display the current time stored in code), or bi-directional.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] Data binding doesn't have any restrictions on types, and it is possible to bind structs, classes, or collections.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] Converters can be used to transpose the values and types being used during binding - for example, binding a textbox to a DateTime property, but using a converter to display the time as a formatted localised date string.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] Most properties on built-in controls can be databound, and custom-made controls can create bindable properties by defining Dependency Properties.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] MVVM, the architectural pattern encouraged by Microsoft for WPF developers, relies heavily on data binding.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] Using templates and styles, developers can define the visuals and structure of UI elements.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] A style is a combination of property settings that can be applied to a UI element with a single property attribute.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] For example, a "blue radio button" style could be created and then be reused on any number of radio button controls throughout the program.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] Styles can alter collections of properties of controls, but are not intended for significant structural changes.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] Templates are a mechanism for defining alternative UI for portions of a WPF application.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] There are several template types available in WPF for different scenarios, but they all have the general purpose of defining the contents, layout and structure of a UI element.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] In WPF, many visual properties can be animated.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] This is exposed through dependency properties, which is the same underlying system that data binding relies on.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] WPF animations are time-based, as opposed to frame-based.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] Animation classes are based on the .NET type of property to be animated.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] For instance, changing the color of an element is done with the ColorAnimation class and animating the width of an element (which is typed as a double) is done with the DoubleAnimation class.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] Animations can be grouped into Storyboards, which are the primary way to start, stop, pause and otherwise manipulate animations.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] WPF natively supports paginated documents.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] It provides the `DocumentViewer` class, which is for reading fixed layout documents.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] The `FlowDocumentReader` class offers different view modes such as per-page or scrollable and also reflows text if the viewing area is resized.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] It supports both the Open XML Paper Specification and Open Packaging Conventions.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] WPF includes a number of text rendering features, including OpenType, TrueType, and OpenType CFF (Compact Font Format) fonts.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] This means that WPF can support a wide number of text features, including ligatures, old-style numerals, swash variants, fraction, superscript and subscript, small caps, ruby characters, glyph substitution, multiple baselines, and kerning.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] WPF handles texts in Unicode, and handles texts independent of global settings, such as system locale.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] In addition, fallback mechanisms are provided to allow writing direction (horizontal versus vertical) handled independent of font name; building international fonts from composite fonts, using a group of single-language fonts; composite fonts embedding.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] Font linking and font fallback information is stored in a portable XML file, using composite font technology.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] The XML file has extension *.CompositeFont*.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] The WPF text engine also supports built-in spell checking.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] It also supports such features as automatic line spacing, enhanced international text, language-guided line breaking, hyphenation, and justification, bitmap effects, transforms, and text effects such as shadows, blur, glow, rotation etc.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] Animated text is also supported; this refers to animated glyphs, as well as real-time changes in position, size, color, and opacity of the text.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] WPF text rendering takes advantage of advances in ClearType technology, such as sub-pixel positioning, natural advance widths, Y-direction anti-aliasing, hardware-accelerated text rendering, as well as aggressive caching of pre-rendered text in video memory.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] ClearType cannot be turned off in older WPF 3.x applications.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] Windows Forms features are possible through the use of the `ElementHost` and `WindowsFormsHost` classes.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] WPF programs, via the P/Invoke feature of the CLR, can access native functionality such calling functions from Windows libraries.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] This allows the ability to communicate and operate other parts of the operating system, including unmanaged libraries.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] WPF supports Windows Ink for pen-based input, and multi-touch input on Windows 7 and above.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] It also supports Microsoft UI Automation to allow developers to create accessible interfaces, and to expose the UI to automated test frameworks.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] Following the success of markup languages for web development, WPF introduced eXtensible Application Markup Language (XAML; /ˈzæməl/), which is based on XML.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] XAML is designed as a more efficient method of developing application user interfaces.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] XAML is a declarative language, meaning the developer (or designer) describes the behavior and integration of components without the use of procedural programming.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] Although it is rare that an entire application will be built completely in XAML, the introduction of XAML allows application designers to more effectively contribute to the application development cycle.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] Using XAML to develop user interfaces also allows for separation of model and view, which is considered a good architectural principle.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] In XAML, elements and attributes map to classes and properties in the underlying APIs.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] As in web development, both layouts and specific themes are well suited to markup, but XAML is not required for either.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] Indeed, all elements of WPF may be coded in a .NET language (C#, VB.NET).
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] The XAML code can ultimately be compiled into a managed assembly in the same way all .NET languages are.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] WPF applications are Windows-only standalone desktop executables.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] Historically, WPF supported compiling to XBAP, a file format intended to be shown in web browsers via a NPAPI plugin, but NPAPI and XBAP support was phased out of support by browsers, and XBAP compilation is now no longer included for WPF for .NET.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] WPF is used to develop Visual Studio, Microsoft's flagship IDE, and was used for developing Microsoft Expression Blend.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] WPF and its layout language, XAML, have influenced multiple other UI frameworks.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] Silverlight (codenamed WPF/E - WPF Everywhere), released in 2007, is a deprecated cross-browser browser plugin.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] Silverlight had a WPF-based implementation, including using XAML for layouting, that supported video, vector graphics, and animations.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] Using add-ons, it was supported on Mozilla Firefox, Internet Explorer 6 and above, Google Chrome 42 and below and Apple Safari.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] Microsoft encouraged developers to stop using Silverlight in 2015, and support was officially ended in 2021.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] After becoming open source in 2018, WPF inspired the development of Avalonia, an open-source .NET cross-platform XAML-based UI framework, distributed under the MIT License.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] While WPF only is intended for Windows, Avalonia also supports builds for web (via WebAssembly), MacOS, Android, iOS, and Linux.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] Avalonia's name references WPF's in-development codename ("Avalon"), and markets itself as "a spiritual successor to WPF".
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] Avalonia is currently used in tools made by Unity, GitHub and JetBrains.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] OpenSilver is framework designed to migrate WPF solutions to web using WebAssembly.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] OpenSilver 3.1, released in December 2024, included a XAML designer for use in Visual Studio Code.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] Developers of WPF applications typically use Microsoft Visual Studio.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] Visual Studio contains a combination XAML editor and WPF visual designer, beginning with Visual Studio 2008.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] Prior to Visual Studio 2008, the WPF designer add-in, codenamed Cider, was the original release of a WYSIWYG editor for creating WPF windows, pages, and user controls.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] It was available for Visual Studio 2005 as a *Visual Studio 2005 extensions for .NET Framework 3.0 CTP* for the initial release of WPF.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] Visual Studio is not strictly required to develop WPF projects, as solutions can be built in the command line using MSBuild.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] Microsoft Blend is a designer-oriented tool that provides an artboard for the creation of WPF applications with 2D and 3D graphics, text and forms content.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] It generates XAML that may be exported into other tools and shares solution (sln files) and project formats (csproj, vbproj) with Microsoft Visual Studio.
[src:wpf-xaml/windows-presentation-foundation] Microsoft Expression Design is a bitmap and 2D-vector graphics tool for exporting to XAML.
